===Noun===
'''byssus''', plural '''byssuses''', derives from [[Hebrew]] ''būṣ'', [[Aramaic]] ''bus'' via [[Greek]] ''βίσσος'' – 'a very fine yellowish [[flax]] and the [[linen]] woven from it', [[Latin]] ''byssus'' – 'fine [[cotton]] or cotton stuff', '[[silk]]' and via [[New Latin]] to '[[sea silk]]'.

# An exceptionally fine and valuable fibre or cloth of ancient times. Originally used for fine flax and linens, its use was later extended to fine cottons, silks, and sea silk.
# The long fine silky [[filament]]s excreted by several [[mollusk]]s (particularly ''Pinna noblis'') by which they attach themselves to the [[sea bed]], from which [[sea silk]] is manufactured.
# The [[stipe]] or [[stem]] of some [[fungi]] which are particularly thin and thread-like.

